          "body": "Jeremiah's response in verses 6-9 is the chapter's intellectual center. He does not simply counter-assert; he invokes a canonical principle. The prophetic tradition from ancient times — Moses, Samuel, Isaiah, Amos, Hosea, Micah — was predominantly a tradition of calamity, war, and pestilence announced against nations and kingdoms (28:8). Peace prophecies were not impossible, but they were rare and always contingent on repentance (cf. Jeremiah 18:7-8). The weight of canonical precedent fell against Hananiah's oracle. The specific burden Jeremiah articulates in verse 9 is the Deuteronomic fulfillment test (Deuteronomy 18:21-22): when the word of the prophet comes to pass, then that prophet will be known as one whom the Lord has truly sent. This is not a counsel of skepticism about all prophecy; it is a specific hermeneutical principle about peace oracles, grounded in both canonical pattern and covenantal law."
