          "title": "The seventh month — fulfilled in the same chapter",
          "body": "Verse 17's four-word report — 'So Hananiah the prophet died in the same year in the seventh month' — is the chapter's theological resolution and its most carefully placed detail. The confrontation occurred in the fifth month (28:1); Hananiah died in the seventh month (28:17): two months elapsed between the public promise and the public death. This compression is unprecedented in the biblical prophetic literature — the fulfillment test Jeremiah had articulated in verse 9 is enacted before the scroll of this chapter ends. The reader does not need to live two years to discover which prophet was true. God applied the criterion within the narrative. The same word shalach (sent) that Jeremiah used to define the true prophet in verse 9 appears again in verse 15 ('the Lord has not sent you') and in verse 16 ('I am about to remove you' — shalach, dismissal as the reversal of commissioning). The chapter closes as it should: with the word verified by event, and with the one who truly spoke for God standing vindicated not by argument but by fulfillment."
